comments.text:
In all seriousness though, regardless of his or anyone else’s opinions on the actual show’s appeal and quality, you’ve also really gotta consider the incredibly rushed production Sonic Underground was forced through (in order for DiC to get song residual checks ASAP, no less) and the impact on all of those people’s morale and wellbeing, at least in terms of the creative burnout and general waining interest that inevitably comes with these situations.

Just try to imagine yourself in their position for a moment; you’re stuck in a rut working on something that for the life of you can’t put your heart into for one reason or another, expected by the corporate higher-ups to pump out one fully completed episode per week or so, and on top of that knowing that the same company turned down your chance to revitalised something you truly hold near your heart. That’s inevitably going to take its toll on anyone, whether they enjoy what they’re working on or not (hence why, by your own admission, the show ended up having its fair share of turd-tier episodes).

Also on a side note, being happy for Ben’s passing (especially considering his battle with cancer) is a really low blow to make, even if it was hyperbolic. You say that like he royally messed with you and your family or something, not like he was just a writer/ story editor for a couple of 90’s Sonic cartoons. I get being passionate about the things you love, but being joyful for a creator’s misfortunes (especially when matters don’t go the way you want) is just going way too far. You’re better than to be like that.
